242
00:12:09,146 --> 00:12:11,827
is pregnant with Jason Blossom's baby.

243
00:12:11,829 --> 00:12:13,429
[ALL MUTTERING]

244
00:12:17,045 --> 00:12:18,705
Polly wouldn't hurt a fly,

245
00:12:18,708 --> 00:12:21,170
let alone the father
of her unborn child.

246
00:12:24,295 --> 00:12:27,062
Polly, darling, if you're watching this,

247
00:12:28,813 --> 00:12:30,245
please come home.

248
00:12:32,950 --> 00:12:35,384
BETTY: Hey, you didn't
have to walk me home.

249
00:12:35,386 --> 00:12:38,633
JUGHEAD: Uh, there's a
killer on the loose, remember?

250
00:12:39,724 --> 00:12:42,658
Besides, isn't this what...

251
00:12:44,228 --> 00:12:45,361
You know...

252
00:12:46,831 --> 00:12:50,899
What people like us,

253
00:12:50,901 --> 00:12:53,529
who've gone through what
we've gone through, do?

254
00:12:56,972 --> 00:12:59,873
What is it? I mean, besides everything.

255
00:13:02,046 --> 00:13:05,114
She wouldn't have run away
if it wasn't for me, Jug.

256
00:13:06,329 --> 00:13:11,189
Betty, your parents were the ones lying
to her, and keeping her in the dark.

257
00:13:12,326 --> 00:13:14,493
You did the right thing
telling her the truth.

258
00:13:16,594 --> 00:13:22,172
It's funny. This isn't the first
time Polly's run away from home.

259
00:13:22,175 --> 00:13:26,101
When she was nine, she and
my mom got in this huge fight,

260
00:13:26,103 --> 00:13:28,237
and she disappeared for hours.

261
00:13:28,239 --> 00:13:30,572
The whole neighborhood
was out looking for her.

262
00:13:30,574 --> 00:13:32,141
How far did she get?

263
00:13:34,745 --> 00:13:35,944
What?

264
00:13:41,154 --> 00:13:43,554
Thank you for walking me home.

265
00:13:43,557 --> 00:13:45,534
I'll call you later. Goodnight.

266
00:13:48,313 --> 00:13:49,612
[THUNDER RUMBLING]

267
00:13:53,030 --> 00:13:55,164
Mom? Dad?

268
00:14:08,412 --> 00:14:10,245
[DOOR CREAKS]

269
00:14:15,586 --> 00:14:17,052
Polly?

270
00:14:19,301 --> 00:14:21,168
It's okay. I'm alone.

271
00:14:22,359 --> 00:14:24,159
Mom and Dad aren't here.

272
00:14:37,341 --> 00:14:38,774
[GASPS]

273
00:14:43,834 --> 00:14:45,501
- [GASPS]
- Shh.

274
00:14:47,660 --> 00:14:51,034
Betty, you have to help me. Please.

275
00:14:54,926 --> 00:14:57,207
How did you get up here
without anyone seeing you?

276
00:14:57,210 --> 00:14:59,400
I wrote the book on getting
in and out of this house.

277
00:14:59,402 --> 00:15:01,402
And Dad still hasn't
fixed the cellar door.

278
00:15:01,404 --> 00:15:03,071
Polly, everyone's worried sick,

279
00:15:03,073 --> 00:15:05,973
why did you leave the home? You
could have really hurt yourself.

280
00:15:05,975 --> 00:15:07,475
I couldn't just stay there,

281
00:15:07,477 --> 00:15:09,863
waiting for someone who
was never gonna show.

282
00:15:09,866 --> 00:15:14,649
Jason and I, we had a plan to go to
this farm, upstate, and raise the baby.

283
00:15:14,651 --> 00:15:16,557
It's where I still want
to go, but I don't

284
00:15:16,560 --> 00:15:18,288
have any money, I don't have anything.

285
00:15:18,291 --> 00:15:19,643
Why don't you just stay here?

286
00:15:19,646 --> 00:15:21,989
Mom and Dad want me to give
the baby up for adoption,

287
00:15:21,991 --> 00:15:24,392
they made that very clear.
And that's not what I want.

288
00:15:24,395 --> 00:15:26,230
Well, this is their grandchild, Polly.

289
00:15:26,233 --> 00:15:27,806
Everyone knows you're pregnant now.

290
00:15:27,809 --> 00:15:29,130
There's no more stigma.

291
00:15:29,132 --> 00:15:30,932
You don't know what they'll do.

292
00:15:31,846 --> 00:15:34,642
And I won't have my baby raised
in a home that doesn't want it.

293
00:15:34,645 --> 00:15:36,704
- Polly...
- [DOOR OPENS]

294
00:15:36,707 --> 00:15:38,272
Give me a few days.

295
00:15:38,274 --> 00:15:41,142
I'll find you someplace
safe, here in Riverdale.

296
00:15:41,144 --> 00:15:44,245
Please, Polly, I cannot lose you again.

297
00:15:45,048 --> 00:15:46,614
[DOOR OPENS AND CLOSES]

298
00:15:50,220 --> 00:15:53,177
This is an upgrade from the
tin can we used to work in.

299
00:15:53,180 --> 00:15:55,757
Wasn't sure you were gonna
take me up on the offer.

300
00:15:55,760 --> 00:15:56,985
Wasn't sure it was real.

301
00:15:56,988 --> 00:15:59,115
I'm not gonna lie to
you, it wasn't my idea.

302
00:15:59,118 --> 00:16:00,091
[CHUCKLES]

303
00:16:00,094 --> 00:16:01,865
The boys came up with this.

304
00:16:03,233 --> 00:16:05,166
But I probably could
have reached out before.

305
00:16:06,569 --> 00:16:09,904
Look, coming back
here isn't easy for me.

306
00:16:09,906 --> 00:16:11,139
But, hell, I...

307
00:16:14,878 --> 00:16:18,546
I just want my son to look at me
and not see a piece of garbage.

308
00:16:19,755 --> 00:16:21,555
Feels like it might be my last shot.

309
00:16:23,504 --> 00:16:25,037
Then let's make it work.

310
00:16:29,492 --> 00:16:31,058
- Thank you.
- Yeah.

311
00:16:31,775 --> 00:16:34,529
Hermione, you remember
FP Jones from high school.

312
00:16:34,531 --> 00:16:36,063
- He's gonna be working with us.
- [CELL PHONE RINGING]

313
00:16:36,065 --> 00:16:37,198
- Hermione.
- Of course.

314
00:16:37,200 --> 00:16:38,633
- It's been forever. Hi.
- Hi.

315
00:16:38,635 --> 00:16:41,469
Excuse me. Yeah, Vic, talk to me.

316
00:16:43,085 --> 00:16:44,651
[DOOR CLOSES]

317
00:16:44,654 --> 00:16:46,441
Look, if this is another shake-down...

318
00:16:46,443 --> 00:16:47,775
No, it's not, we're good.

319
00:16:47,777 --> 00:16:49,210
Your convict husband settled-up.

320
00:16:49,213 --> 00:16:51,932
I think he got the message after
you got our little care-package.

321
00:16:51,935 --> 00:16:53,581
Why are you even here?

322
00:16:53,583 --> 00:16:55,950
My son asked me to try
and go straight, okay?

323
00:16:55,952 --> 00:16:57,218
You gonna make that hard on me?

324
00:16:57,220 --> 00:16:58,953
Dudley-Do-Right doesn't
know I'm a Serpent,

325
00:16:58,955 --> 00:17:01,489
so I'd appreciate it if
you keep that to yourself.

326
00:17:01,491 --> 00:17:03,702
Because here's the thing about snakes.

327
00:17:03,705 --> 00:17:06,694
You don't step on them,
they got no reason to bite.

328
00:17:10,066 --> 00:17:12,600
BETTY: Mom, Dad, when we find Polly,

329
00:17:12,603 --> 00:17:15,336
she's gonna live with us, right?

330
00:17:15,338 --> 00:17:21,108
At this point, there's no reason
to hide or banish her, is there?

331
00:17:21,111 --> 00:17:23,911
Oh, of course not,
honey. She's welcome back.

332
00:17:27,417 --> 00:17:28,816
Where will the baby sleep?

333
00:17:28,819 --> 00:17:32,320
Sweetie, um, we've talked
to your sister about this,

334
00:17:32,323 --> 00:17:35,243
and she's agreed to put
the baby up for adoption.

335
00:17:35,246 --> 00:17:36,724
Polly did?

336
00:17:38,108 --> 00:17:41,075
This is a very difficult decision
for a young mother to make,

337
00:17:41,078 --> 00:17:44,665
but given the
circumstances, it's the best.

338
00:17:45,135 --> 00:17:48,215
- The only...
- The only option.

339
00:17:51,237 --> 00:17:52,370
Why do you ask, honey?

340
00:17:55,144 --> 00:17:58,045
No reason. Just curious.

341
00:17:59,327 --> 00:18:01,415
I don't want Polly to run away.

342
00:18:01,417 --> 00:18:03,451
But if she can't live at home, then...

343
00:18:03,453 --> 00:18:06,621
I don't know, I can
rent her an apartment.

344
00:18:06,623 --> 00:18:07,855
Let me talk to my mom.

345
00:18:07,858 --> 00:18:10,997
No, you have your own stuff
you're dealing with right now, V.

346
00:18:11,000 --> 00:18:14,450
Betty, Polly needs doctors,
she needs prenatal vitamins...

347
00:18:14,453 --> 00:18:16,325
She needs her family.

348
00:18:19,602 --> 00:18:20,768
[SIGHS]

349
00:18:21,671 --> 00:18:23,094
What do you want, Cheryl?

350
00:18:23,773 --> 00:18:25,373
What we both want.

351
00:18:28,077 --> 00:18:29,677
For the baby to be safe.

352
00:18:30,813 --> 00:18:32,647
- How can I help?
- [LAUGHS]

353
00:18:32,649 --> 00:18:35,483
You can't, I don't trust you, Cheryl.

354
00:18:35,486 --> 00:18:38,619
So don't trust me. Watch me like a hawk.

355
00:18:38,621 --> 00:18:40,288
Tell me the barest minimum.

356
00:18:40,290 --> 00:18:41,756
But let me help you help Polly.

357
00:18:41,758 --> 00:18:43,021
You think Polly's crazy.

358
00:18:43,024 --> 00:18:46,928
I do, I think she's crazier than a
serial killer on bath-salts, but so what?

359
00:18:47,746 --> 00:18:50,982
She's carrying Jason's
baby. That trumps everything.

360
00:18:51,902 --> 00:18:53,034
Do you know where she is?

361
00:18:54,203 --> 00:18:55,770
If I did, I wouldn't tell you.

362
00:18:55,772 --> 00:18:58,139
- Oh, my God, you do.
- What? No.

363
00:18:58,141 --> 00:19:01,223
Wow, you are literally the
worst liar I've ever encountered.

364
00:19:01,226 --> 00:19:02,743
Spare me the details, Betty.

365
00:19:02,746 --> 00:19:06,317
Just tell me how I can be of assistance
to my darling nephew or niece.

366
00:19:06,320 --> 00:19:09,221
Okay, uh, Polly needs money.

367
00:19:09,981 --> 00:19:12,366
For a safe place to live.
And for medical stuff.

368
00:19:12,369 --> 00:19:14,655
Cash? Is that all?

369
00:19:14,658 --> 00:19:16,090
I can talk to my mom and dad.

370
00:19:16,092 --> 00:19:17,458
What? No, Cheryl.

371
00:19:17,460 --> 00:19:19,427
Jason's baby is a game-changer.

372
00:19:19,430 --> 00:19:21,629
We're all on the same team now.

373
00:19:25,134 --> 00:19:27,805
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

374
00:19:27,808 --> 00:19:30,488
- Oh, how was your first day back?
- FP: Oh, it was great.

375
00:19:30,491 --> 00:19:33,573
Your dad is the hardest-working
guy on the crew, as always.

376
00:19:33,576 --> 00:19:35,606
- [CHUCKLES]
- Oh, in that case,

377
00:19:35,609 --> 00:19:37,243
why don't we celebrate
to mark the occasion?

378
00:19:37,245 --> 00:19:38,249
Yeah, Juggy and I were thinking

379
00:19:38,251 --> 00:19:40,170
the four of us could
have dinner or something.

380
00:19:40,173 --> 00:19:41,748
Uh, tonight? I don't know...

381
00:19:41,751 --> 00:19:42,950
I'm game if you're game.

382
00:19:43,877 --> 00:19:45,110
On me.

383
00:19:46,577 --> 00:19:47,710
[SIGHS]

384
00:19:49,904 --> 00:19:51,303
FP: [LAUGHING] Anyway...

385
00:19:51,306 --> 00:19:54,562
We spent the whole summer
fixing up that old VW bus.

386
00:19:54,564 --> 00:19:55,696
Yeah.

387
00:19:55,698 --> 00:19:57,365
Remember what we called it, Fred?

388
00:19:57,367 --> 00:19:59,607
BOTH: The Shaggin' Wagon.

389
00:19:59,610 --> 00:20:01,373
- FP: The Shaggin' Wagon.
- [FRED LAUGHS]

390
00:20:01,376 --> 00:20:03,070
This was before your dad had game.

391
00:20:03,072 --> 00:20:04,772
Senior Year, he started a band,

392
00:20:04,774 --> 00:20:06,273
and then the girls were all over him.

393
00:20:06,276 --> 00:20:07,608
We were awful.

394
00:20:07,610 --> 00:20:08,576
Yeah, yeah, we were.

395
00:20:08,578 --> 00:20:09,877
- [LAUGHS]
- Oh.

396
00:20:09,880 --> 00:20:13,681
But it was great. Best time of my life.

397
00:20:14,998 --> 00:20:19,967
You know, your dad was what is
commonly known as a BMOC, Jughead.

398
00:20:19,970 --> 00:20:21,990
- FP: Come on. The hell I was.
- In what way?

399
00:20:21,993 --> 00:20:23,146
Football, for one.

400
00:20:23,149 --> 00:20:26,328
He single-handedly defeated our
arch-rivals, the Baxter High Ravens.

401
00:20:26,330 --> 00:20:29,565
He doesn't care about that
stuff, Fred. Football, sports.

402
00:20:29,568 --> 00:20:31,333
Takes after his mom in that respect,

403
00:20:31,335 --> 00:20:32,668
and I mean that as a compliment.

404
00:20:32,671 --> 00:20:34,537
I'd rather see you spending your time

405
00:20:34,539 --> 00:20:37,973
writing, thinking up
stories, you still do that?

406
00:20:37,976 --> 00:20:40,576
Nose in a book? Typing away?

407
00:20:40,579 --> 00:20:43,467
Yeah, yeah, Jughead works on
the school paper with Betty.

408
00:20:43,470 --> 00:20:44,635
Betty?

409
00:20:45,416 --> 00:20:47,316
- Ooh.
- [TAPS TABLE]

410
00:20:47,319 --> 00:20:49,584
Who is Betty? Is that your girlfriend?

411
00:20:49,587 --> 00:20:50,719
She's...

412
00:20:50,722 --> 00:20:54,315
I wanna know more about the band.

413
00:20:54,318 --> 00:20:56,525
What was the name of the band?

414
00:20:56,527 --> 00:20:57,626
[FP LAUGHS]

415
00:20:57,628 --> 00:20:58,761
Ah, yeah.

416
00:20:58,763 --> 00:21:00,729
It was called The Fred Heads.

417
00:21:00,731 --> 00:21:01,897
[LAUGHS]

418
00:21:01,899 --> 00:21:03,032
Wait, the what now?

419
00:21:03,034 --> 00:21:05,301
Yeah, that's why it
doesn't come up very often.

420
00:21:05,303 --> 00:21:06,602
Oh, thanks, Pop.

421
00:21:07,228 --> 00:21:10,066
Oh, come on, Fred. This
was supposed to be my treat.

422
00:21:10,069 --> 00:21:11,548
Hey, you get it next time.

423
00:21:13,044 --> 00:21:15,511
Hey, excuse me. Pop?

424
00:21:16,314 --> 00:21:18,013
We invited you guys out. Let me pay.

425
00:21:18,016 --> 00:21:19,748
Put your damn money away.

426
00:21:19,750 --> 00:21:21,116
FP, take it easy.

427
00:21:23,621 --> 00:21:24,853
You owe me this.

428
00:21:26,090 --> 00:21:27,957
- Yeah, sure.
- Yeah.

429
00:21:27,959 --> 00:21:29,625
Go ahead. You get this one.

430
00:21:29,627 --> 00:21:32,361
You know, if I'd have known, I
would have gotten another milkshake.

431
00:21:37,168 --> 00:21:38,534
Where are you going?

432
00:21:39,133 --> 00:21:41,370
And don't say clubbing,
it's a school night.

433
00:21:41,372 --> 00:21:42,838
But that's exactly where I'm going,

434
00:21:42,840 --> 00:21:44,039
and do you know why?

435
00:21:44,042 --> 00:21:45,808
Because I have a Get
Out of Jail Free card.

436
00:21:45,810 --> 00:21:49,244
[SIGHS] Okay, Ronnie, enough.

437
00:21:49,247 --> 00:21:51,887
Checkmate. What do you want?

438
00:21:51,890 --> 00:21:53,182
For you to admit what you did.

439
00:21:53,184 --> 00:21:56,452
Fine. I kissed Fred Andrews.

440
00:21:56,455 --> 00:21:58,074
No, Mom, the other thing.

441
00:21:58,077 --> 00:21:59,955
It involves you forging my signature

442
00:21:59,957 --> 00:22:02,758
to get Fred Andrews that stupid
contract to build on Dad's land.

443
00:22:02,761 --> 00:22:04,560
Veronica, I asked you to sign that...

444
00:22:04,562 --> 00:22:07,214
You broke the law, Mom,
and you used me to do it.

445
00:22:07,217 --> 00:22:09,732
When Daddy finds out, he's
gonna think I betrayed him.

446
00:22:09,734 --> 00:22:10,866
He won't, I will tell him.

447
00:22:10,869 --> 00:22:13,703
Really? When? Right now?

448
00:22:13,706 --> 00:22:15,438
Because I'll cancel my plans for that.

449
00:22:15,441 --> 00:22:17,338
You know it doesn't work that way.

450
00:22:17,341 --> 00:22:19,938
In that case, I'll talk to you
later, my friends are waiting.

451
00:22:22,146 --> 00:22:23,756
Ronnie, do not go out that door.

452
00:22:23,759 --> 00:22:25,530
- [DOOR CLOSES]
- Veronica!

453
00:22:34,276 --> 00:22:36,843
[CLUB MUSIC PLAYING]

454
00:23:04,955 --> 00:23:06,162
JOSIE: Ah!

455
00:23:06,164 --> 00:23:07,564
[ALL LAUGHING]

456
00:23:07,567 --> 00:23:10,633
JOSIE: Mmm-mmm, girl.
You better hydrate.

457
00:23:10,635 --> 00:23:13,882
You practically left your
body on the dance floor.

458
00:23:13,885 --> 00:23:15,572
- [SIGHS]
- VERONICA: I wish, Josie.

459
00:23:15,574 --> 00:23:17,807
I wish I could leave my body sometimes.

460
00:23:17,809 --> 00:23:19,816
Leave Riverdale, leave everything.

461
00:23:19,819 --> 00:23:21,211
Is any of this helping?

462
00:23:21,213 --> 00:23:25,059
Going out, going <i>Black Swan,</i> any of it?

463
00:23:26,952 --> 00:23:28,885
When my dad got arrested,

464
00:23:29,355 --> 00:23:32,489
the police, the lawyers,
the judge, the courts,

465
00:23:32,491 --> 00:23:34,290
they took everything from us.

466
00:23:34,293 --> 00:23:39,344
Our houses, our cars, our
club memberships, our yacht,

467
00:23:40,371 --> 00:23:43,105
even, I'm not kidding,
the clothes off our backs.

468
00:23:44,269 --> 00:23:45,401
[SIGHS]

469
00:23:45,404 --> 00:23:49,743
Anyway, my mom sat me down
on the edge of my canopy bed

470
00:23:49,746 --> 00:23:52,008
and she told me not to cry.

471
00:23:52,010 --> 00:23:54,878
Because there was one
thing in this world

472
00:23:54,880 --> 00:23:57,147
that no one could ever take from me.

473
00:23:57,149 --> 00:23:59,215
- Not ever.
- Your trust fund?

474
00:24:00,457 --> 00:24:02,023
My name, Reggie.

475
00:24:02,026 --> 00:24:04,721
Which, after telling me
no one would ever take it,

476
00:24:04,723 --> 00:24:07,457
that is exactly what she did.

477
00:24:09,131 --> 00:24:10,760
Like it meant nothing.

478
00:24:12,545 --> 00:24:14,045
It was nothing.

479
00:24:16,688 --> 00:24:18,154
Like I was nothing.

480
00:24:25,877 --> 00:24:27,944
[ARCHIE JAMMING WITH FP]

481
00:24:30,472 --> 00:24:32,138
Damn, Hoss, you're good.

482
00:24:32,141 --> 00:24:33,818
Way better than your dad.

483
00:24:33,821 --> 00:24:36,039
Hey, does Fred keep any beer in there?

484
00:24:36,042 --> 00:24:37,207
Uh...

485
00:24:37,210 --> 00:24:39,825
Dad, don't you think it's
a little late? Kinda...

486
00:24:39,828 --> 00:24:42,559
Oh, yeah, yeah. No, it's all right.

487
00:24:42,561 --> 00:24:44,761
You know, I got a big
day tomorrow anyway.

488
00:24:47,532 --> 00:24:49,265
Hey, Mr. Jones, before you go,

489
00:24:49,268 --> 00:24:51,073
- can I ask you a question?
- Yeah.

490
00:24:51,076 --> 00:24:54,003
Earlier tonight, you
said my dad owed you.

491
00:24:54,005 --> 00:24:55,271
What did you mean by that?

492
00:24:56,582 --> 00:24:59,083
Hey, Archie, why don't we
quit while we're ahead?

493
00:25:00,212 --> 00:25:02,312
It's just... I mean,
it's just a question.

494
00:25:03,348 --> 00:25:05,081
Did something happen between you two?

495
00:25:06,151 --> 00:25:09,118
It's ancient history,
but your dad and me, we...

496
00:25:10,188 --> 00:25:12,021
We started Andrews
Construction together.

497
00:25:12,023 --> 00:25:13,389
You and my dad were partners?

498
00:25:13,391 --> 00:25:15,391
[CHUCKLES] He wouldn't call us that.

499
00:25:16,561 --> 00:25:18,995
Anyway, we, uh...

500
00:25:19,798 --> 00:25:22,098
We struggled at first.

501
00:25:22,101 --> 00:25:25,668
Fred, he just had you and
your mom to provide for,

502
00:25:25,670 --> 00:25:29,906
I had Jughead and Jellybean and
their mom and hospital bills.

503
00:25:30,518 --> 00:25:33,643
So I took some odd jobs that
weren't exactly on the level.

504
00:25:33,645 --> 00:25:36,212
And sure enough, one of 'em
landed me in some hot water,

505
00:25:37,115 --> 00:25:41,517
and your dad was good
enough to bail me out.

506
00:25:42,920 --> 00:25:46,256
But then he said we should part
ways. That I was a liability.

507
00:25:46,258 --> 00:25:50,126
Made me sign a paper saying the bail
money was him buying me out of the company.

508
00:25:50,129 --> 00:25:52,695
Never mind that my share of the business

509
00:25:52,697 --> 00:25:55,732
was worth probably 10 times that, easy.

510
00:25:59,068 --> 00:26:00,334
So that was that.

511
00:26:01,373 --> 00:26:04,073
He went his way, and I went mine.

512
00:26:05,911 --> 00:26:08,544
You know, I think I need something
a little harder than beer.

513
00:26:11,693 --> 00:26:13,493
Clifford and I were so relieved

514
00:26:13,496 --> 00:26:16,927
when Cheryl told us that Polly
and the baby are safe and sound.

515
00:26:16,930 --> 00:26:18,588
CLIFFORD: And money
won't be a problem, Betty.

516
00:26:18,590 --> 00:26:21,758
Not now, not ever. Not with us.

517
00:26:21,761 --> 00:26:25,348
PENELOPE: But, of course, we don't
want to just offer financial support,

518
00:26:25,351 --> 00:26:27,669
we want to give Polly
all the emotional support

519
00:26:27,672 --> 00:26:29,706
that a young mother-to-be needs.

520
00:26:30,936 --> 00:26:33,069
Where is Polly staying now?

521
00:26:35,340 --> 00:26:37,640
I'd rather not say yet.

522
00:26:37,642 --> 00:26:40,008
[CHUCKLES] You understand.

523
00:26:40,011 --> 00:26:43,947
Of course, but you and Polly are
part of the Blossom family now,

524
00:26:43,949 --> 00:26:47,684
and we will protect you ferociously.

525
00:26:49,587 --> 00:26:51,287
All you have to do is trust.

526
00:26:52,524 --> 00:26:53,823
Will you?

527
00:27:00,498 --> 00:27:03,633
Jughead, what your dad
told us... I had no idea.

528
00:27:03,636 --> 00:27:05,335
Me neither.

529
00:27:05,337 --> 00:27:06,903
Illuminating, isn't it?

530
00:27:09,007 --> 00:27:11,841
[SIGHS] My dad must've
had a good reason.

531
00:27:11,853 --> 00:27:13,810
For screwing over my dad?

532
00:27:13,812 --> 00:27:15,545
FP: Are you ready to roll, Jugs?

533
00:27:21,886 --> 00:27:23,319
[KEYS JANGLING]

534
00:27:23,989 --> 00:27:25,421
[SIGHS] See you tomorrow.

535
00:27:31,376 --> 00:27:33,829
I'm sorry, Ms. Lodge, but
your card's been declined.

536
00:27:33,832 --> 00:27:35,431
Really?

537
00:27:35,434 --> 00:27:38,249
And let me guess, it's
been reported stolen.

538
00:27:38,252 --> 00:27:39,769
It has, in fact.

539
00:27:39,772 --> 00:27:41,637
We're supposed to call the cops.

540
00:27:41,639 --> 00:27:42,999
Yeah, sure. Call the cops.

541
00:27:43,002 --> 00:27:44,769
We'll be happy to tell
them how old we are.

542
00:27:44,772 --> 00:27:48,101
Or I could call my mom, the mayor.

543
00:27:49,914 --> 00:27:51,581
This should cover it.

544
00:27:55,720 --> 00:27:56,853
[JOSIE LAUGHS]

545
00:27:56,855 --> 00:27:58,987
Veronica, did your mom cut you off?

546
00:27:58,990 --> 00:28:00,289
She did.

547
00:28:00,292 --> 00:28:02,392
- And that's a good thing?
- Oh, Reggie.

548
00:28:02,394 --> 00:28:04,660
This is how we Lodge women roll.

549
00:28:05,196 --> 00:28:08,375
We feint, we parry, we
approach, we retreat.

550
00:28:08,378 --> 00:28:10,774
We're like a cobra
and a mongoose dancing.

551
00:28:11,603 --> 00:28:13,870
She blinked, which means, I suspect,

552
00:28:13,872 --> 00:28:16,072
that Hermione Lodge
is ready to negotiate.

553
00:28:16,441 --> 00:28:18,674
Wow. Oh.

554
00:28:19,477 --> 00:28:22,445
I'll sleep right here on this couch,

555
00:28:22,447 --> 00:28:24,247
you can have the bedroom. [SIGHS]

556
00:28:24,249 --> 00:28:25,569
I'm not gonna take your bed, Dad.

557
00:28:25,956 --> 00:28:28,704
It wouldn't be the first
time I crashed on this thing.

558
00:28:28,707 --> 00:28:30,219
Ah, thank you.

559
00:28:30,919 --> 00:28:33,692
If you stay... Are
you? You're gonna stay?

560
00:28:35,226 --> 00:28:36,793
Don't be late for school.

561
00:28:36,795 --> 00:28:38,394
It's all right.

562
00:28:38,397 --> 00:28:40,711
I'm already way ahead in all my classes.

563
00:28:40,714 --> 00:28:42,632
Hey, I talked to Mom.

564
00:28:43,835 --> 00:28:46,903
She got a job at a call center
to pay for her online classes.

565
00:28:46,905 --> 00:28:50,406
I guess she's finally
going after her GED.

566
00:28:50,409 --> 00:28:53,429
Jellybean is helping her study.

567
00:28:53,432 --> 00:28:56,512
By the way, Jellybean
wants to go with JB now.

568
00:28:56,515 --> 00:28:58,414
She thinks it sounds cooler.

569
00:28:59,304 --> 00:29:03,439
She's 10 years old and
listens to Pink Floyd on vinyl,

570
00:29:03,442 --> 00:29:05,416
I don't think she could get any cooler.

571
00:29:13,731 --> 00:29:15,264
[KNOCKING ON DOOR]

572
00:29:15,266 --> 00:29:17,852
Hey, bud. How was your jam session?

573
00:29:17,855 --> 00:29:21,369
It was great, until FP told us

574
00:29:21,372 --> 00:29:24,139
you forced him out of the
company he helped found.

575
00:29:24,142 --> 00:29:28,910
That's his story, wanna hear mine, hmm?

576
00:29:28,913 --> 00:29:30,336
FP was a mess.

577
00:29:30,339 --> 00:29:33,082
He was stealing from the company
and selling stuff on the side.

578
00:29:33,084 --> 00:29:35,972
All things considered,
I was pretty generous.

579
00:29:35,975 --> 00:29:38,028
So generous you didn't
give him a second chance?

580
00:29:38,031 --> 00:29:39,430
Of course I did.

581
00:29:39,433 --> 00:29:42,859
You have no idea how many times
I bailed that man out of jail.

582
00:29:42,861 --> 00:29:46,254
Son, when someone is drowning,

583
00:29:46,257 --> 00:29:49,465
you can try to save them, but not if
they're gonna drag you down with them.

584
00:29:49,467 --> 00:29:52,368
I did the best I could for my family.

585
00:29:53,338 --> 00:29:54,704
For you.

586
00:29:57,742 --> 00:30:00,877
Yeah, and who cares if
Jughead ended up drowning, too.

587
00:30:14,086 --> 00:30:16,853
Reporting my American
Excess card as stolen,

588
00:30:16,856 --> 00:30:18,155
well-played.

589
00:30:18,753 --> 00:30:20,956
I thought you might appreciate that.

590
00:30:20,959 --> 00:30:24,447
Now, <i>mija.</i> I've done things to upset you.

591
00:30:24,450 --> 00:30:26,345
You've done things to upset me.

592
00:30:26,348 --> 00:30:29,339
So we're gonna deal with this
exactly as your father would like.

593
00:30:29,342 --> 00:30:31,253
With a negotiation. I'll start.

594
00:30:32,744 --> 00:30:34,710
I am working with Mr. Andrews,

595
00:30:34,713 --> 00:30:37,815
and yes, we are developing
feelings for each other.

596
00:30:37,818 --> 00:30:39,743
But I can't tell you what it means yet

597
00:30:39,745 --> 00:30:40,977
because I don't know myself.

598
00:30:40,979 --> 00:30:42,548
What about Daddy?

599
00:30:42,551 --> 00:30:47,551
He has made certain decisions that have
distanced him from me, and this family.

600
00:30:47,553 --> 00:30:49,820
So I need to make certain decisions

601
00:30:49,822 --> 00:30:54,062
about my life moving
forward, what I want.

602
00:30:54,065 --> 00:30:58,227
So, what, you want me
to accept your affair?

603
00:30:58,230 --> 00:31:00,163
Until we get more information, yes.

604
00:31:00,966 --> 00:31:03,266
That is what I'm asking you to accept.

605
00:31:05,034 --> 00:31:07,636
Fine. Agreed. Now, my turn.

606
00:31:07,639 --> 00:31:08,738
I'm listening.

607
00:31:08,740 --> 00:31:11,039
Whatever is happening with you and Fred,

608
00:31:11,042 --> 00:31:12,541
can't happen under this roof.

609
00:31:12,544 --> 00:31:13,510
Agreed.

610
00:31:14,459 --> 00:31:16,958
And you have to come clean to
Daddy about forging my signature.

611
00:31:16,961 --> 00:31:18,662
Lodge Industries needs to partner

612
00:31:18,665 --> 00:31:20,403
with legitimate
businesses, not criminals.

613
00:31:20,406 --> 00:31:23,483
Understood. I don't want
Daddy thinking I betrayed him.

614
00:31:24,795 --> 00:31:26,889
I will tell him about the forgery.

615
00:31:26,892 --> 00:31:28,308
And say it was all my doing.

616
00:31:28,311 --> 00:31:30,756
And in the meantime,
the online shopping,

617
00:31:30,759 --> 00:31:32,395
the clubbing,

618
00:31:33,332 --> 00:31:34,798
all that stops.

619
00:31:36,154 --> 00:31:37,620
- Yes?
- Yes.

620
00:31:52,610 --> 00:31:54,810
- Hey.
- Hey.

621
00:31:59,955 --> 00:32:02,728
Uh, what's up?

622
00:32:03,715 --> 00:32:06,016
I'm going to need you to come
down to the station with me.

623
00:32:16,575 --> 00:32:17,674
Call my dad.

624
00:32:17,676 --> 00:32:19,246
- Yeah, yeah.
- Of course.

625
00:32:24,038 --> 00:32:26,366
SHERIFF KELLER: Forensics
came back on the car.

626
00:32:26,369 --> 00:32:30,153
Despite the fire, we were able to
pull a pair of prints off the trunk.

627
00:32:30,156 --> 00:32:31,454
Yours and Betty's.

628
00:32:31,456 --> 00:32:33,089
This is, of course, no surprise.

629
00:32:33,092 --> 00:32:36,787
But what did surprise me was this.

630
00:32:36,790 --> 00:32:38,361
Your prints were on file

631
00:32:38,364 --> 00:32:41,024
from an incident that
happened six years ago,

632
00:32:41,027 --> 00:32:42,400
where you spent some time with the

633
00:32:42,403 --> 00:32:45,589
Riverdale Juvenile
Delinquent Center for...

634
00:32:48,354 --> 00:32:51,388
"Attempting to burn down
Riverdale Elementary School."

635
00:32:51,391 --> 00:32:53,374
I was playing with matches,

636
00:32:53,377 --> 00:32:56,093
and that's a pretty tenuous
connection for a sheriff.

637
00:32:56,096 --> 00:32:58,788
Well, Principal
Weatherbee also allowed me

638
00:32:58,791 --> 00:33:00,874
to have a look at your school records.

639
00:33:00,877 --> 00:33:04,386
You have a long and
rough history, Mr. Jones.

640
00:33:04,389 --> 00:33:05,854
Bullied a lot.

641
00:33:05,857 --> 00:33:08,413
Yeah, my name is Jughead.

642
00:33:08,416 --> 00:33:10,334
By the football team, in particular.

643
00:33:10,953 --> 00:33:13,696
I can only assume that would
have included Jason Blossom.

644
00:33:13,699 --> 00:33:15,098
So how about this?

645
00:33:15,100 --> 00:33:18,434
How about you tell me your
whereabouts on the week of July 11th?

646
00:33:18,437 --> 00:33:21,076
This is crazy. You think I...

647
00:33:23,495 --> 00:33:25,996
Jughead. A kid like you,

648
00:33:25,999 --> 00:33:28,610
raised on the wrong side of
the tracks by a deadbeat dad,

649
00:33:28,613 --> 00:33:31,105
bullied by kids like Jason Blossom.

650
00:33:32,332 --> 00:33:34,165
Who wouldn't want to lash out at that?

651
00:33:36,221 --> 00:33:38,121
I'm not talking to you anymore.

652
00:33:38,124 --> 00:33:39,723
I want a lawyer.

653
00:33:45,715 --> 00:33:50,199
Cheryl, you've called
Polly a party girl.

654
00:33:50,202 --> 00:33:52,621
Have you seen her take drugs? Firsthand?

655
00:33:54,678 --> 00:33:59,241
Um... I'm not sure, why?

656
00:33:59,244 --> 00:34:00,810
Due diligence.

657
00:34:00,812 --> 00:34:02,412
We wouldn't want an unfit mother

658
00:34:02,414 --> 00:34:04,921
raising our grandchild now, would we?

659
00:34:07,855 --> 00:34:09,488
No, of course not.

660
00:34:22,186 --> 00:34:24,419
I didn't do it, Betty,
you have to believe me.

661
00:34:24,422 --> 00:34:28,428
Of course, I was with you,
and I know who you are.

662
00:34:28,431 --> 00:34:30,540
Those <i>Paradise Lost</i>
kids went to death row

663
00:34:30,542 --> 00:34:31,641
because they wore black

664
00:34:31,643 --> 00:34:33,510
and they listened to Metallica.

665
00:34:33,513 --> 00:34:35,491
I don't wanna become a scapegoat.

666
00:34:35,494 --> 00:34:37,312
I'm not gonna let that happen.

667
00:34:37,315 --> 00:34:38,415
[SIGHS]

668
00:34:38,417 --> 00:34:41,640
All the evidence against
you is circumstantial.

669
00:34:41,643 --> 00:34:44,453
We're gonna get you out of here.

670
00:34:44,456 --> 00:34:46,089
[SNIFFLES]

671
00:34:46,092 --> 00:34:47,751
Is my dad here yet?

672
00:34:47,754 --> 00:34:49,860
Archie's here with his dad.

673
00:34:49,863 --> 00:34:51,402
They're talking to the Sheriff.

674
00:34:53,187 --> 00:34:54,986
No one knows where your dad is.

675
00:34:55,634 --> 00:34:57,667
Jughead's not helping himself in there.

676
00:34:57,669 --> 00:35:00,203
I asked him for an alibi,
and he just gave me lip.

677
00:35:01,557 --> 00:35:02,856
He was working for me.

678
00:35:03,515 --> 00:35:05,208
Yeah, the week of July 11th, was it?

679
00:35:05,211 --> 00:35:07,468
Yeah, I had him tear
down some drywall for me.

680
00:35:10,115 --> 00:35:12,916
You can provide me with
documentation to support that?

681
00:35:14,474 --> 00:35:16,407
I have to check my time cards.

682
00:35:25,597 --> 00:35:26,729
Jughead!

683
00:35:27,661 --> 00:35:29,060
I'm sorry.

684
00:35:29,063 --> 00:35:31,294
I came as soon as I got your messages.

685
00:35:31,297 --> 00:35:33,424
My phone, the friggin' battery.

686
00:35:33,427 --> 00:35:35,094
I forgot to plug it in last night.

687
00:35:37,208 --> 00:35:39,341
- What the hell happened?
- Nothing.

688
00:35:39,344 --> 00:35:41,010
It's fine now.

689
00:35:41,012 --> 00:35:42,967
Mr. Andrews took care of it.

690
00:35:44,116 --> 00:35:46,843
What jacked-up crap did they
accuse you of in there, huh?

691
00:35:46,846 --> 00:35:48,486
Those bastards trying
to throw you in jail

692
00:35:48,489 --> 00:35:50,467
like they did your old
man? Well, screw that.

693
00:35:51,423 --> 00:35:53,543
I will rip Keller a new one
for trying to pull that...

694
00:35:53,546 --> 00:35:54,591
- FP, settle down.
- Hey! Hey!

695
00:35:54,593 --> 00:35:57,093
This is my son, he is my son, Fred!

696
00:35:57,096 --> 00:35:58,869
You'd do the same for your boy.

697
00:35:58,872 --> 00:36:00,163
Dad.

698
00:36:01,266 --> 00:36:03,766
Don't make things worse.

699
00:36:05,937 --> 00:36:07,070
Please.

700
00:36:11,114 --> 00:36:12,380
Yeah.

701
00:36:14,012 --> 00:36:15,477
Yeah, all right, then.

702
00:36:15,480 --> 00:36:19,110
You, uh, coming home with me?

703
00:36:21,746 --> 00:36:23,979
He can stay with us, Mr. Jones.

704
00:36:25,185 --> 00:36:26,484
We already offered.

705
00:36:28,173 --> 00:36:29,405
Is that what you want?

706
00:36:34,884 --> 00:36:36,284
Maybe that's for the best.

707
00:36:36,287 --> 00:36:37,834
If you don't mind, Fred.

708
00:36:39,774 --> 00:36:41,240
Whatever you want, FP.

709
00:36:42,641 --> 00:36:44,007
It's between the two of you.

710
00:36:45,912 --> 00:36:47,245
I'll go with you, Dad.

711
00:36:49,047 --> 00:36:50,213
[SNIFFLES]

712
00:36:57,389 --> 00:36:59,222
Son, listen to me.

713
00:37:02,947 --> 00:37:04,813
I'm gonna do what you want,

714
00:37:06,145 --> 00:37:07,963
get my act together.

715
00:37:07,966 --> 00:37:10,741
I'm gonna get your
mom and Jellybean home

716
00:37:10,744 --> 00:37:12,411
so we're all under the same roof.

717
00:37:13,338 --> 00:37:15,405
I promise. But I...

718
00:37:15,407 --> 00:37:17,240
I just need a little time to do that.

719
00:37:17,242 --> 00:37:20,903
Not a lot, not long, a
month, two at the most.

720
00:37:22,113 --> 00:37:23,246
Hey.

721
00:37:24,749 --> 00:37:27,951
And then we'll be back
on track, all right?

722
00:37:29,588 --> 00:37:31,287
You...

723
00:37:31,923 --> 00:37:33,656
You believe that, don't you?

724
00:37:37,976 --> 00:37:40,643
Yeah, I believe you, Dad.

725
00:37:48,740 --> 00:37:49,872
[SIGHS]

726
00:37:51,843 --> 00:37:54,145
[CHUCKLES] All right.

727
00:38:18,526 --> 00:38:19,959
Any minute now.

728
00:38:21,796 --> 00:38:23,262
How do you feel?

729
00:38:25,367 --> 00:38:26,833
Partnering with Andrews Construction

730
00:38:26,836 --> 00:38:29,489
was the right decision to make.

731
00:38:30,912 --> 00:38:33,212
And your father will
either see that or he won't.

732
00:38:34,776 --> 00:38:36,576
Either way, I can live
with the consequences.

733
00:38:38,813 --> 00:38:40,113
[PHONE RINGS]

734
00:38:42,617 --> 00:38:43,816
[PHONE BEEPS]

735
00:38:44,157 --> 00:38:45,690
Hello.

736
00:38:45,693 --> 00:38:47,787
OPERATOR: <i>You're receiving a
call from</i> [MUFFLED] <i>Penitentiary.</i>

737
00:38:47,789 --> 00:38:49,222
<i>Will you accept the charges?</i>

738
00:38:49,224 --> 00:38:50,880
I'll accept the charges.

739
00:39:00,268 --> 00:39:01,968
Looks like you've done this before.

740
00:39:02,871 --> 00:39:06,606
Yeah, well, FP's got
his tricks, I got mine.

741
00:39:06,609 --> 00:39:09,208
Maybe I should've given him
another chance back then.

742
00:39:09,210 --> 00:39:12,612
Either way, Jughead doesn't
deserve what's happening to him.

743
00:39:12,615 --> 00:39:14,330
It's the least I can do.

744
00:39:16,317 --> 00:39:17,750
[SIGHS]

745
00:39:17,752 --> 00:39:19,642
The Blossoms should be here soon.

746
00:39:19,645 --> 00:39:23,155
Once we've talked things through
with them, we'll call Mom and Dad.

747
00:39:24,659 --> 00:39:25,825
Are you nervous?

748
00:39:26,928 --> 00:39:28,361
I'm thankful.

749
00:39:29,060 --> 00:39:32,031
At the home, the Sisters said
each of us had a guardian angel.

750
00:39:33,001 --> 00:39:35,302
- You're mine, Betty.
- [DOOR OPENS]

751
00:39:40,375 --> 00:39:41,674
Cheryl...

752
00:39:43,638 --> 00:39:44,770
[SIGHS]

753
00:39:49,117 --> 00:39:51,150
I'm so sorry about Jason,

754
00:39:51,153 --> 00:39:52,781
I know how much you loved him.

755
00:39:56,943 --> 00:39:59,076
And he always talked about
how much he loved you.

756
00:40:02,711 --> 00:40:04,745
Cheryl, where are your mom and aad?

757
00:40:08,282 --> 00:40:10,115
You have to leave. Now.

758
00:40:10,939 --> 00:40:12,819
My parents, I don't think
they want to help you.

759
00:40:12,822 --> 00:40:14,040
What are you talking about?

760
00:40:14,042 --> 00:40:15,639
They want you out of the picture, Polly.

761
00:40:15,641 --> 00:40:17,008
It's not safe for you with them.

762
00:40:18,293 --> 00:40:20,024
It's not safe for JayJay's baby.

763
00:40:22,048 --> 00:40:24,448
Where am I supposed to go?
I can't go back to the attic.

764
00:40:24,451 --> 00:40:26,318
No. You don't have to, Polly.

765
00:40:26,321 --> 00:40:29,422
And don't worry about my mom,
Betty, she'll want to help.

766
00:40:29,425 --> 00:40:31,845
Of course you can stay.
As long as you need.

767
00:40:32,560 --> 00:40:34,160
Anything for Alice Cooper's daughters.

768
00:40:34,163 --> 00:40:35,862
[SIGHS] Thank you, Mrs. Lodge.

769
00:40:35,864 --> 00:40:37,697
- And thank you, Veronica.
- Yeah.

770
00:40:37,699 --> 00:40:39,365
You're welcome, girls.

771
00:40:39,368 --> 00:40:41,434
And please, now that we're
going to be roommates, Polly,

772
00:40:41,436 --> 00:40:42,602
it's Hermione.

773
00:40:42,604 --> 00:40:44,270
Come, sit, make yourself at home.

774
00:40:53,014 --> 00:40:54,480
I'm sorry about my dad,

775
00:40:55,517 --> 00:40:57,682
and your dad.

776
00:40:57,685 --> 00:40:59,318
I'm not giving up on him, Arch.

777
00:41:00,922 --> 00:41:02,288
Not yet.

778
00:41:04,593 --> 00:41:06,233
You think he'll show
up for work tomorrow?

779
00:41:07,443 --> 00:41:10,344
You never know. I hope.

780
00:41:13,334 --> 00:41:17,003
JUGHEAD: <i>Hope. A word so close to home,</i>

781
00:41:17,006 --> 00:41:19,105
<i>and as tricky.</i>

782
00:41:21,574 --> 00:41:24,075
<i>As much as we wanted
Jason's killer caught,</i>

783
00:41:24,078 --> 00:41:27,502
<i>and the town, our home,
to feel safe again,</i>

784
00:41:27,505 --> 00:41:32,208
<i>with every day that passed, our
hopes dimmed more and more.</i>

785
00:41:32,211 --> 00:41:34,687
<i>There's that old, cliched saying,</i>

786
00:41:34,690 --> 00:41:37,023
<i>“It's darkest before the dawn.”</i>

787
00:41:37,492 --> 00:41:38,825
<i>But sometimes...</i>

788
00:41:40,461 --> 00:41:43,129
<i>There's just darkness.</i>

789
